	   <tr><td colspan=2>I agree with you 100%.&nbsp;&nbsp;Politeness and imagination can work wonders in game.  And I think that’s the case because so few people take the time to use them.  And to be honest, I think laziness is the culprit.  Most people, by nature, tend to be lazy.  Just look at the English language.  How many people say taxicab in a conversation compared to taxi or airplane instead of plane?  We have an annoying tendency to take the quickest rout between two points instead of pausing to smell the gingerbread.  And in an online game this seems to be amplified.  So when someone speaks in full words and, heaven forbid, says something witty, we tend to take notice.  <br><br>One of the main reasons I play a druid is because I enjoy helping people.  I never have fun playing classes where I can’t SoW or heal people.  I love getting KEI and going to a newbie zone and buffing the heck out of low-level characters.  So someone asking for SoW or other buffs shouldn’t bother me.  But rude people tick me off really fast.  And it sometimes amazes me how many of them are out there. But sometimes someone will surprise me.  One of my biggest pet peeves is begging.  I’ve given away lots of equipment to low-level characters.  Again, I think its fun.  But I swore from the very start that I would NEVER give ANYTHING to a beggar.  Then, a couple of months ago, someone actually role-played his begging in such a fresh and imaginative way that I actually took him to the bank and gave him stuff.  <br><br>So hopefully people will take heed and follow your advice.  Politeness and imagination are more likely to get you what you want than rudeness and brevity.  And in my opinion they’re a lot more fun.  <br><br>&nbsp;<br><b>Namir Shadowstalker</b><br>Wood Elf Ranger, 51st Season<br><b>Calabar Silverthorn</b><br>Wood Elf Druid, 51st Season<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 50th Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b></td></tr>
